#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:3810
msgid "Choice of the appropriate base class for a package"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:3811
msgid ""
"In most cases packagers don't have to worry about the selection of the right "
"base class for a package, as ``spack create`` will make the appropriate "
"choice on their behalf. In those rare cases where manual intervention is "
"needed we need to stress that a package base class depends on the *build "
"system* being used, not the language of the package. For example, a Python "
"extension installed with CMake would ``extends(\"python\")`` and subclass "
"from :class:`~spack.build_systems.cmake.CMakePackage`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:3820
msgid "Overriding builder methods"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:3822
msgid ""
"Build-system \"phases\" have default implementations that fit most of the "
"common cases:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:3824
msgid ""
"    def configure(self, pkg, spec, prefix):\n"
"        \"\"\"Run \"configure\", with the arguments specified by the builder "
"and an\n"
"        appropriately set prefix.\n"
"        \"\"\"\n"
"        options = getattr(self.pkg, \"configure_flag_args\", [])\n"
"        options += [\"--prefix={0}\".format(prefix)]\n"
"        options += self.configure_args()\n"
"\n"
"        with fs.working_dir(self.build_directory, create=True):\n"
"            pkg.module.configure(*options)\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:3828
msgid ""
"It is usually sufficient for a packager to override a few build system "
"specific helper methods or attributes to provide, for instance, configure "
"arguments:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:3832
msgid ""
"    def configure_args(self):\n"
"        spec = self.spec\n"
"        args = [\"--enable-c++\"]\n"
"\n"
"        if spec.satisfies(\"%cce@9:\"):\n"
"            args.append(\"LDFLAGS=-rtlib=compiler-rt\")\n"
"\n"
"        if (\n"
"            spec.satisfies(\"%clang\")\n"
"            or spec.satisfies(\"%aocc\")\n"
"            or spec.satisfies(\"%arm\")\n"
"            or spec.satisfies(\"%fj\")\n"
"        ) and not spec.satisfies(\"platform=darwin\"):\n"
"            args.append(\"LDFLAGS=-rtlib=compiler-rt\")\n"
"\n"
"        if spec.satisfies(\"%intel@:18\"):\n"
"            args.append(\"CFLAGS=-no-gcc\")\n"
"\n"
"        if \"+sigsegv\" in spec:\n"
"            args.append(\"--with-libsigsegv-prefix={0}\"."
"format(spec[\"libsigsegv\"].prefix))\n"
"        else:\n"
"            args.append(\"--without-libsigsegv-prefix\")\n"
"\n"
"        # https://lists.gnu.org/archive/html/bug-m4/2016-09/msg00002.html\n"
"        arch = spec.architecture\n"
"        if arch.platform == \"darwin\" and arch.os == \"sierra\" and "
"\"%gcc\" in spec:\n"
"            args.append(\"ac_cv_type_struct_sched_param=yes\")\n"
"\n"
"        return args\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:3836
msgid ""
"Each specific build system has a list of attributes and methods that can be "
"overridden to fine-tune the installation of a package without overriding an "
"entire phase. To have more information on them the place to go is the API "
"docs of the :py:mod:`~.spack.build_systems` module."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:3843
msgid "Overriding an entire phase"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:3845
msgid ""
"Sometimes it is necessary to override an entire phase. If the ``package.py`` "
"contains a single class recipe, see :ref:`package_class_structure`, then the "
"signature for a phase is:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:3849
msgid ""
"class Openjpeg(CMakePackage):\n"
"    def install(self, spec, prefix):\n"
"        ..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:3855
msgid "regardless of the build system. The arguments for the phase are:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:3857
msgid "``self``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:3858
msgid ""
"This is the package object, which extends ``CMakePackage``. For API docs on "
"Package objects, see :py:class:`Package <spack.package_base.PackageBase>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:3862
msgid "``spec``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:3863
msgid ""
"This is the concrete spec object created by Spack from an abstract spec "
"supplied by the user.  It describes what should be installed.  It will be of "
"type :py:class:`Spec <spack.spec.Spec>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:3867
msgid "``prefix``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:3868
msgid ""
"This is the path that your install method should copy build targets into.  "
"It acts like a string, but it's actually its own special type, :py:class:"
"`Prefix <spack.util.prefix.Prefix>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:3872
msgid ""
"The arguments ``spec`` and ``prefix`` are passed only for convenience, as "
"they always correspond to ``self.spec`` and ``self.spec.prefix`` "
"respectively."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:3875
msgid ""
"If the ``package.py`` has build instructions in a separate :ref:`builder "
"class <multiple_build_systems>`, the signature for a phase changes slightly:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:3878
msgid ""
"class CMakeBuilder(spack.build_systems.cmake.CMakeBuilder):\n"
"    def install(self, pkg, spec, prefix):\n"
"        ..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:3884
msgid ""
"In this case the package is passed as the second argument, and ``self`` is "
"the builder instance."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:3888
msgid "Mixin base classes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:3890
msgid ""
"Besides build systems, there are other cases where common metadata and "
"behavior can be extracted and reused by many packages. For instance, "
"packages that depend on ``Cuda`` or ``Rocm``, share common dependencies and "
"constraints. To factor these attributes into a single place, Spack provides "
"a few mixin classes in the ``spack.build_systems`` module:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:3898
msgid ":class:`~spack.build_systems.cuda.CudaPackage`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:3898
msgid "A helper class for packages that use CUDA"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:3901
msgid ":class:`~spack.build_systems.rocm.ROCmPackage`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:3901
msgid "A helper class for packages that use ROCm"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:3904
msgid ":class:`~spack.build_systems.gnu.GNUMirrorPackage`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:3904
msgid "A helper class for GNU packages"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:3906
msgid ":class:`~spack.build_systems.python.PythonExtension`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:3906
msgid "A helper class for Python extensions"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:3909
msgid ":class:`~spack.build_systems.sourceforge.SourceforgePackage`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:3909
msgid "A helper class for packages from sourceforge.org"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:3912
msgid ":class:`~spack.build_systems.sourceware.SourcewarePackage`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:3912
msgid "A helper class for packages from sourceware.org"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:3915
msgid ":class:`~spack.build_systems.xorg.XorgPackage`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:3915
msgid "A helper class for x.org packages"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:3919
msgid ""
"These classes should be used by adding them to the inheritance tree of the "
"package that needs them, for instance:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:3922
msgid ""
"class Cp2k(MakefilePackage, CudaPackage):\n"
"    \"\"\"CP2K is a quantum chemistry and solid state physics software "
"package\n"
"    that can perform atomistic simulations of solid state, liquid, "
"molecular,\n"
"    periodic, material, crystal, and biological systems\n"
"    \"\"\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:3930
msgid ""
"In the example above ``Cp2k`` inherits all the conflicts and variants that "
"``CudaPackage`` defines."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:3936
msgid "Multiple build systems"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:3938
msgid ""
"There are cases where a package actively supports two build systems, or "
"changes build systems as it evolves, or needs different build systems on "
"different platforms. Spack allows dealing with these cases by splitting the "
"build instructions into separate builder classes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:3942
msgid ""
"For instance, software that supports two build systems unconditionally "
"should derive from both ``*Package`` base classes, and declare the possible "
"use of multiple build systems using a directive:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:3946
msgid ""
"class Example(CMakePackage, AutotoolsPackage):\n"
"\n"
"    variant(\"my_feature\", default=True)\n"
"\n"
"    build_system(\"cmake\", \"autotools\", default=\"cmake\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:3954
msgid ""
"In this case the software can be built with both ``autotools`` and "
"``cmake``. Since the package supports multiple build systems, it is "
"necessary to declare which one is the default."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:3957
msgid "Additional build instructions are split into separate builder classes:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:3959
msgid ""
"class CMakeBuilder(spack.build_systems.cmake.CMakeBuilder):\n"
"    def cmake_args(self):\n"
"        return [\n"
"            self.define_from_variant(\"MY_FEATURE\", \"my_feature\")\n"
"        ]\n"
"\n"
"class AutotoolsBuilder(spack.build_systems.autotools.AutotoolsBuilder):\n"
"    def configure_args(self):\n"
"        return self.with_or_without(\"my-feature\", variant=\"my_feature\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:3971
msgid ""
"In this example, ``spack install example +feature build_sytem=cmake``  will "
"pick the ``CMakeBuilder`` and invoke ``cmake -DMY_FEATURE:BOOL=ON``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:3974
msgid ""
"Similarly, ``spack install example +feature build_system=autotools`` will "
"pick the  ``AutotoolsBuilder`` and invoke ``./configure --with-my-feature``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:3977
msgid ""
"Dependencies are always specified in the package class. When some "
"dependencies depend on the choice of the build system, it is possible to use "
"when conditions as usual:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:3981
msgid ""
"class Example(CMakePackage, AutotoolsPackage):\n"
"\n"
"    build_system(\"cmake\", \"autotools\", default=\"cmake\")\n"
"\n"
"    # Runtime dependencies\n"
"    depends_on(\"ncurses\")\n"
"    depends_on(\"libxml2\")\n"
"\n"
"    # Lowerbounds for cmake only apply when using cmake as the build system\n"
"    with when(\"build_system=cmake\"):\n"
"        depends_on(\"cmake@3.18:\", when=\"@2.0:\", type=\"build\")\n"
"        depends_on(\"cmake@3:\", type=\"build\")\n"
"\n"
"    # Specify extra build dependencies used only in the configure script\n"
"    with when(\"build_system=autotools\"):\n"
"        depends_on(\"perl\", type=\"build\")\n"
"        depends_on(\"pkgconfig\", type=\"build\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4001
msgid ""
"Very often projects switch from one build system to another, or add support "
"for a new build system from a certain version, which means that the choice "
"of the build system typically depends on a version range. Those situations "
"can be handled by using conditional values in the ``build_system`` directive:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4006
msgid ""
"class Example(CMakePackage, AutotoolsPackage):\n"
"\n"
"    build_system(\n"
"        conditional(\"cmake\", when=\"@0.64:\"),\n"
"        conditional(\"autotools\", when=\"@:0.63\"),\n"
"        default=\"cmake\",\n"
"    )"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4016
msgid ""
"In the example the directive impose a change from ``Autotools`` to ``CMake`` "
"going from ``v0.63`` to ``v0.64``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4019
msgid ""
"The ``build_system`` can be used as an ordinary variant, which also means "
"that it can be used in ``depends_on`` statements. This can be useful when a "
"package *requires* that its dependency has a CMake config file, meaning that "
"the dependent can only build when the dependency is built with CMake, and "
"not Autotools. In that case, you can force the choice of the build system in "
"the dependent:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4025
msgid ""
"class Dependent(CMakePackage):\n"
"\n"
"    depends_on(\"example build_system=cmake\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4036
msgid "The build environment"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4038
msgid ""
"In general, you should not have to do much differently in your install "
"method than you would when installing a package on the command line. In "
"fact, you may need to do *less* than you would on the command line."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4042
msgid ""
"Spack tries to set environment variables and modify compiler calls so that "
"it *appears* to the build system that you're building with a standard system "
"install of everything.  Obviously that's not going to cover *all* build "
"systems, but it should make it easy to port packages to Spack if they use a "
"standard build system.  Usually with autotools or cmake, building and "
"installing is easy.  With builds that use custom Makefiles, you may need to "
"add logic to modify the makefiles."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4050
msgid ""
"The remainder of the section covers the way Spack's build environment works."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4055
msgid "Forking ``install()``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4057
msgid ""
"To give packagers free reign over their install environment, Spack forks a "
"new process each time it invokes a package's ``install()`` method. This "
"allows packages to have a sandboxed build environment, without impacting the "
"environments ofother jobs that the main Spack process runs. Packages are "
"free to change the environment or to modify Spack internals, because each "
"``install()`` call has its own dedicated process."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4066
msgid "Environment variables"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4068
msgid ""
"Spack sets a number of standard environment variables that serve two "
"purposes:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4071
msgid "Make build systems use Spack's compiler wrappers for their builds."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4072
msgid "Allow build systems to find dependencies more easily"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4074
msgid "The Compiler environment variables that Spack sets are:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4077
msgid "Variable"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4079
msgid "``CC``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4079
msgid "C compiler"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4080
msgid "``CXX``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4080
msgid "C++ compiler"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4081
msgid "``F77``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4081
msgid "Fortran 77 compiler"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4082
msgid "``FC``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4082
msgid "Fortran 90 and above compiler"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4085
msgid ""
"Spack sets these variables so that they point to *compiler wrappers*. These "
"are covered in :ref:`their own section <compiler-wrappers>` below."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4089
msgid ""
"All of these are standard variables respected by most build systems. If your "
"project uses ``Autotools`` or ``CMake``, then it should pick them up "
"automatically when you run ``configure`` or ``cmake`` in the ``install()`` "
"function.  Many traditional builds using GNU Make and BSD make also respect "
"these variables, so they may work with these systems."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4096
msgid ""
"If your build system does *not* automatically pick these variables up from "
"the environment, then you can simply pass them on the command line or use a "
"patch as part of your build process to get the correct compilers into the "
"project's build system.  There are also some file editing commands you can "
"use -- these are described later in the `section on file manipulation <file-"
"manipulation_>`_."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4103
msgid ""
"In addition to the compiler variables, these variables are set before "
"entering ``install()`` so that packages can locate dependencies easily:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4108
msgid "``PATH``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4108
msgid "Set to point to ``/bin`` directories of dependencies"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4109
msgid "``CMAKE_PREFIX_PATH``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4109
msgid "Path to dependency prefixes for CMake"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4110
msgid "``PKG_CONFIG_PATH``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4110
msgid "Path to any pkgconfig directories for dependencies"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4111
msgid "``PYTHONPATH``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4111
msgid "Path to site-packages dir of any python dependencies"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4114
msgid ""
"``PATH`` is set up to point to dependencies ``/bin`` directories so that you "
"can use tools installed by dependency packages at build time. For example, "
"``$MPICH_ROOT/bin/mpicc`` is frequently used by dependencies of ``mpich``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4119
msgid ""
"``CMAKE_PREFIX_PATH`` contains a colon-separated list of prefixes where "
"``cmake`` will search for dependency libraries and headers. This causes all "
"standard CMake find commands to look in the paths of your dependencies, so "
"you *do not* have to manually specify arguments like ``-DDEPENDENCY_DIR=/"
"path/to/dependency`` to ``cmake``.  More on this is `in the CMake "
"documentation <http://www.cmake.org/cmake/help/v3.0/variable/"
"CMAKE_PREFIX_PATH.html>`_."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4126
msgid ""
"``PKG_CONFIG_PATH`` is for packages that attempt to discover dependencies "
"using the GNU ``pkg-config`` tool.  It is similar to ``CMAKE_PREFIX_PATH`` "
"in that it allows a build to automatically discover its dependencies."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4131
msgid ""
"If you want to see the environment that a package will build with, or if you "
"want to run commands in that environment to test them out, you can use the :"
"ref:`cmd-spack-build-env` command, documented below."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4138
msgid "Failing the build"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4140
msgid ""
"Sometimes you don't want a package to successfully install unless some "
"condition is true.  You can explicitly cause the build to fail from "
"``install()`` by raising an ``InstallError``, for example:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4144
msgid ""
"if spec.architecture.startswith(\"darwin\"):\n"
"    raise InstallError(\"This package does not build on Mac OS X!\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4153
msgid "Shell command functions"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4155
msgid "Recall the install method from ``libelf``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4157
msgid ""
"    def install(self, spec, prefix):\n"
"        make(\"install\", parallel=False)\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4161
msgid ""
"Normally in Python, you'd have to write something like this in order to "
"execute shell commands:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4164
msgid ""
"import subprocess\n"
"subprocess.check_call(\"configure\", \"--prefix={0}\".format(prefix))"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4169
msgid ""
"We've tried to make this a bit easier by providing callable wrapper objects "
"for some shell commands.  By default, ``configure``, ``cmake``, and ``make`` "
"wrappers are are provided, so you can call them more naturally in your "
"package files."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4174
msgid "If you need other commands, you can use ``which`` to get them:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4176
msgid ""
"sed = which(\"sed\")\n"
"sed(\"s/foo/bar/\", filename)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4181
msgid "The ``which`` function will search the ``PATH`` for the application."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4183
msgid ""
"Callable wrappers also allow spack to provide some special features. For "
"example, in Spack, ``make`` is parallel by default, and Spack figures out "
"the number of cores on your machine and passes an appropriate value for ``-"
"j<numjobs>`` when it calls ``make`` (see the ``parallel`` `package attribute "
"<attribute_parallel>`).  In a package file, you can supply a keyword "
"argument, ``parallel=False``, to the ``make`` wrapper to disable parallel "
"make.  In the ``libelf`` package, this allows us to avoid race conditions in "
"the library's build system."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4195
msgid "Compiler flags"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4197
msgid ""
"Compiler flags set by the user through the Spec object can be passed to the "
"build in one of three ways. By default, the build environment injects these "
"flags directly into the compiler commands using Spack's compiler wrappers. "
"In cases where the build system requires knowledge of the compiler flags, "
"they can be registered with the build system by alternatively passing them "
"through environment variables or as build system arguments. The flag_handler "
"method can be used to change this behavior."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4206
msgid ""
"Packages can override the flag_handler method with one of three built-in "
"flag_handlers. The built-in flag_handlers are named ``inject_flags``, "
"``env_flags``, and ``build_system_flags``. The ``inject_flags`` method is "
"the default. The ``env_flags`` method puts all of the flags into the "
"environment variables that ``make`` uses as implicit variables (\"CFLAGS\", "
"\"CXXFLAGS\", etc.). The ``build_system_flags`` method adds the flags as "
"arguments to the invocation of ``configure`` or ``cmake``, respectively."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4218
msgid ""
"Passing compiler flags using build system arguments is only supported for "
"CMake and Autotools packages. Individual packages may also differ in whether "
"they properly respect these arguments."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4222
msgid ""
"Individual packages may also define their own ``flag_handler`` methods. The "
"``flag_handler`` method takes the package instance (``self``), the name of "
"the flag, and a list of the values of the flag. It will be called on each of "
"the six compiler flags supported in Spack. It should return a triple of "
"``(injf, envf, bsf)`` where ``injf`` is a list of flags to inject via the "
"Spack compiler wrappers, ``envf`` is a list of flags to set in the "
"appropriate environment variables, and ``bsf`` is a list of flags to pass to "
"the build system as arguments."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4234
msgid ""
"Passing a non-empty list of flags to ``bsf`` for a build system that does "
"not support build system arguments will result in an error."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4238
msgid "Here are the definitions of the three built-in flag handlers:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4240
msgid ""
"def inject_flags(pkg, name, flags):\n"
"    return (flags, None, None)\n"
"\n"
"def env_flags(pkg, name, flags):\n"
"    return (None, flags, None)\n"
"\n"
"def build_system_flags(pkg, name, flags):\n"
"    return (None, None, flags)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4253
msgid ""
"Returning ``[]`` and ``None`` are equivalent in a ``flag_handler`` method."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4256
msgid ""
"Packages can override the default behavior either by specifying one of the "
"built-in flag handlers,"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4259
msgid "flag_handler = env_flags"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4263
msgid ""
"or by implementing the flag_handler method. Suppose for a package ``Foo`` we "
"need to pass ``cflags``, ``cxxflags``, and ``cppflags`` through the "
"environment, the rest of the flags through compiler wrapper injection, and "
"we need to add ``-lbar`` to ``ldlibs``. The following flag handler method "
"accomplishes that."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4269
msgid ""
"def flag_handler(self, name, flags):\n"
"    if name in [\"cflags\", \"cxxflags\", \"cppflags\"]:\n"
"        return (None, flags, None)\n"
"    elif name == \"ldlibs\":\n"
"        flags.append(\"-lbar\")\n"
"    return (flags, None, None)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4278
msgid ""
"Because these methods can pass values through environment variables, it is "
"important not to override these variables unnecessarily (E.g. setting "
"``env[\"CFLAGS\"]``) in other package methods when using non-default flag "
"handlers. In the ``setup_environment`` and ``setup_dependent_environment`` "
"methods, use the ``append_flags`` method of the ``EnvironmentModifications`` "
"class to append values to a list of flags whenever the flag handler is "
"``env_flags``. If the package passes flags through the environment or the "
"build system manually (in the install method, for example), we recommend "
"using the default flag handler, or removing manual references and "
"implementing a custom flag handler method that adds the desired flags to "
"export as environment variables or pass to the build system. Manual flag "
"passing is likely to interfere with the ``env_flags`` and "
"``build_system_flags`` methods."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4293
msgid ""
"In rare circumstances such as compiling and running small unit tests, a "
"package developer may need to know what are the appropriate compiler flags "
"to enable features like ``OpenMP``, ``c++11``, ``c++14`` and alike. To that "
"end the compiler classes in ``spack`` implement the following "
"**properties**: ``openmp_flag``, ``cxx98_flag``, ``cxx11_flag``, "
"``cxx14_flag``, and ``cxx17_flag``, which can be accessed in a package by "
"``self.compiler.cxx11_flag`` and alike. Note that the implementation is such "
"that if a given compiler version does not support this feature, an error "
"will be produced. Therefore package developers can also use these properties "
"to assert that a compiler supports the requested feature. This is handy when "
"a package supports additional variants like"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4305
msgid ""
"variant(\"openmp\", default=True, description=\"Enable OpenMP support.\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4313
msgid "Blas, Lapack and ScaLapack libraries"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4315
msgid ""
"Multiple packages provide implementations of ``Blas``, ``Lapack`` and "
"``ScaLapack`` routines.  The names of the resulting static and/or shared "
"libraries differ from package to package. In order to make the ``install()`` "
"method independent of the choice of ``Blas`` implementation, each package "
"which provides it implements ``@property def blas_libs(self):`` to return an "
"object of `LibraryList <https://spack.readthedocs.io/en/latest/llnl.util."
"html#llnl.util.filesystem.LibraryList>`_ type which simplifies usage of a "
"set of libraries. The same applies to packages which provide ``Lapack`` and "
"``ScaLapack``. Package developers are requested to use this interface. "
"Common usage cases are:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4326
msgid "Space separated list of full paths"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4328
msgid ""
"lapack_blas = spec[\"lapack\"].libs + spec[\"blas\"].libs\n"
"options.append(\n"
"   \"--with-blas-lapack-lib={0}\".format(lapack_blas.joined())\n"
")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4335
msgid "Names of libraries and directories which contain them"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4337
msgid ""
"blas = spec[\"blas\"].libs\n"
"options.extend([\n"
"  \"-DBLAS_LIBRARY_NAMES={0}\".format(\";\".join(blas.names)),\n"
"  \"-DBLAS_LIBRARY_DIRS={0}\".format(\";\".join(blas.directories))\n"
"])"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4345
msgid "Search and link flags"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4347
msgid ""
"math_libs = spec[\"scalapack\"].libs + spec[\"lapack\"].libs + "
"spec[\"blas\"].libs\n"
"options.append(\n"
"  \"-DMATH_LIBS:STRING={0}\".format(math_libs.ld_flags)\n"
")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4355
msgid ""
"For more information, see documentation of `LibraryList <https://spack."
"readthedocs.io/en/latest/llnl.util.html#llnl.util.filesystem.LibraryList>`_ "
"class."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4364
msgid "Prefix objects"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4366
msgid ""
"Spack passes the ``prefix`` parameter to the install method so that you can "
"pass it to ``configure``, ``cmake``, or some other installer, e.g.:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4370
msgid "configure(\"--prefix={0}\".format(prefix))"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4374
msgid ""
"For the most part, prefix objects behave exactly like strings.  For packages "
"that do not have their own install target, or for those that implement it "
"poorly (like ``libdwarf``), you may need to manually copy things into "
"particular directories under the prefix.  For this, you can refer to "
"standard subdirectories without having to construct paths yourself, e.g.:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4381
msgid ""
"def install(self, spec, prefix):\n"
"    mkdirp(prefix.bin)\n"
"    install(\"foo-tool\", prefix.bin)\n"
"\n"
"    mkdirp(prefix.include)\n"
"    install(\"foo.h\", prefix.include)\n"
"\n"
"    mkdirp(prefix.lib)\n"
"    install(\"libfoo.a\", prefix.lib)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4394
msgid ""
"Attributes of this object are created on the fly when you request them, so "
"any of the following will work:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4398
msgid "Prefix Attribute"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4398
msgid "Location"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4400
msgid "``prefix.bin``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4400
msgid "``$prefix/bin``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4401
msgid "``prefix.lib64``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4401
msgid "``$prefix/lib64``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4402
msgid "``prefix.share.man``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4402
msgid "``$prefix/share/man``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4403
msgid "``prefix.foo.bar.baz``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4403
msgid "``$prefix/foo/bar/baz``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4406
msgid ""
"Of course, this only works if your file or directory is a valid Python "
"variable name. If your file or directory contains dashes or dots, use "
"``join`` instead:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4410
msgid "prefix.lib.join(\"libz.a\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4419
msgid "Spec objects"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4421
msgid ""
"When ``install`` is called, most parts of the build process are set up for "
"you.  The correct version's tarball has been downloaded and expanded.  "
"Environment variables like ``CC`` and ``CXX`` are set to point to the "
"correct compiler and version.  An install prefix has already been selected "
"and passed in as ``prefix``.  In most cases this is all you need to get "
"``configure``, ``cmake``, or another install working correctly."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4429
msgid ""
"There will be times when you need to know more about the build "
"configuration.  For example, some software requires that you pass special "
"parameters to ``configure``, like ``--with-libelf=/path/to/libelf`` or ``--"
"with-mpich``.  You might also need to supply special compiler flags "
"depending on the compiler.  All of this information is available in the spec."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4440
msgid "Testing spec constraints"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4442
msgid ""
"You can test whether your spec is configured a certain way by using the "
"``satisfies`` method.  For example, if you want to check whether the "
"package's version is in a particular range, you can use specs to do that, e."
"g.:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4447
msgid ""
"configure_args = [\n"
"    \"--prefix={0}\".format(prefix)\n"
"]\n"
"\n"
"if spec.satisfies(\"@1.2:1.4\"):\n"
"    configure_args.append(\"CXXFLAGS='-DWITH_FEATURE'\")\n"
"\n"
"configure(*configure_args)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4458
msgid "This works for compilers, too:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4460
msgid ""
"if spec.satisfies(\"%gcc\"):\n"
"    configure_args.append(\"CXXFLAGS='-g3 -O3'\")\n"
"if spec.satisfies(\"%intel\"):\n"
"    configure_args.append(\"CXXFLAGS='-xSSE2 -fast'\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4467
msgid "Or for combinations of spec constraints:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4469
msgid ""
"if spec.satisfies(\"@1.2%intel\"):\n"
"    tty.error(\"Version 1.2 breaks when using Intel compiler!\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4474
msgid "You can also do similar satisfaction tests for dependencies:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4476
msgid ""
"if spec.satisfies(\"^dyninst@8.0\"):\n"
"    configure_args.append(\"CXXFLAGS=-DSPECIAL_DYNINST_FEATURE\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4481
msgid ""
"This could allow you to easily work around a bug in a particular dependency "
"version."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4484
msgid ""
"You can use ``satisfies()`` to test for particular dependencies, e.g. ``foo."
"satisfies(\"^openmpi@1.2\")`` or ``foo.satisfies(\"^mpich\")``, or you can "
"use Python's built-in ``in`` operator:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4488
msgid ""
"if \"libelf\" in spec:\n"
"    print \"this package depends on libelf\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4493
msgid ""
"This is useful for virtual dependencies, as you can easily see what "
"implementation was selected for this build:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4496
msgid ""
"if \"openmpi\" in spec:\n"
"    configure_args.append(\"--with-openmpi\")\n"
"elif \"mpich\" in spec:\n"
"    configure_args.append(\"--with-mpich\")\n"
"elif \"mvapich\" in spec:\n"
"    configure_args.append(\"--with-mvapich\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4505
msgid "It's also a bit more concise than satisfies."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4509
msgid ""
"The ``satisfies()`` method tests whether this spec has, at least, all the "
"constraints of the argument spec, while ``in`` tests whether a spec or any "
"of its dependencies satisfy the provided spec."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4512
msgid ""
"If the provided spec is anonymous (e.g., \":1.2:\", \"+shared\") or has the "
"same name as the spec being checked, then ``in`` works the same as "
"``satisfies()``; however, use of ``satisfies()`` is more intuitive."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4518
msgid "Architecture specifiers"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4520
msgid ""
"As mentioned in :ref:`support-for-microarchitectures` each node in a "
"concretized spec object has an architecture attribute which is a triplet of "
"``platform``, ``os`` and ``target``. Each of these three items can be "
"queried to take decisions when configuring, building or installing a package."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4527
msgid "Querying the platform and the operating system"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4529
msgid ""
"Sometimes the actions to be taken to install a package might differ "
"depending on the platform we are installing for. If that is the case we can "
"use conditionals:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4532
msgid ""
"if spec.platform == \"darwin\":\n"
"    # Actions that are specific to Darwin\n"
"    args.append(\"--darwin-specific-flag\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4538
msgid ""
"and branch based on the current spec platform. If we need to make a package "
"directive conditional on the platform we can instead employ the usual spec "
"syntax and pass the corresponding constraint to the appropriate argument of "
"that directive:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4542
msgid ""
"class Libnl(AutotoolsPackage):\n"
"\n"
"    conflicts(\"platform=darwin\", msg=\"libnl requires FreeBSD or Linux\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4548
msgid ""
"Similar considerations are also valid for the ``os`` part of a spec's "
"architecture. For instance:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4551
msgid ""
"class Glib(AutotoolsPackage)\n"
"\n"
"    patch(\"old-kernels.patch\", when=\"os=centos6\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4557
msgid "will apply the patch only when the operating system is Centos 6."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4561
msgid ""
"Even though experienced Python programmers might recognize that there are "
"other ways to retrieve information on the platform:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4564
msgid ""
"if sys.platform == \"darwin\":\n"
"    # Actions that are specific to Darwin\n"
"    args.append(\"--darwin-specific-flag\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4570
msgid ""
"querying the spec architecture's platform should be considered the "
"preferred. The key difference is that a query on ``sys.platform``, or "
"anything similar, is always bound to the host on which the interpreter "
"running Spack is located and as such it won't work correctly in environments "
"where cross-compilation is required."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4577
msgid "Querying the target microarchitecture"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4579
msgid ""
"The third item of the architecture tuple is the ``target`` which abstracts "
"the information on the CPU microarchitecture. A list of all the targets "
"known to Spack can be obtained via the command line:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4585
msgid ""
"Within directives each of the names above can be used to match a particular "
"target:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4587
msgid ""
"class Julia(Package):\n"
"    # This patch is only applied on icelake microarchitectures\n"
"    patch(\"icelake.patch\", when=\"target=icelake\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4593
msgid ""
"It's also possible to select all the architectures belonging to the same "
"family using an open range:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4596
msgid ""
"class Julia(Package):\n"
"    # This patch is applied on all x86_64 microarchitectures.\n"
"    # The trailing colon that denotes an open range of targets\n"
"    patch(\"generic_x86_64.patch\", when=\"target=x86_64:\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4603
msgid ""
"in a way that resembles what was shown in :ref:`versions-and-fetching` for "
"versions. Where ``target`` objects really shine though is when they are used "
"in methods called at configure, build or install time. In that case we can "
"test targets for supported features, for instance:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4608
msgid ""
"if spec.satisfies(\"target=avx512\"):\n"
"    args.append(\"--with-avx512\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4613
msgid ""
"The snippet above will append the ``--with-avx512`` item to a list of "
"arguments only if the corresponding feature is supported by the current "
"target. Sometimes we need to take different actions based on the "
"architecture family and not on the specific microarchitecture. In those "
"cases we can check the ``family`` attribute:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4618
msgid ""
"if spec.target.family == \"ppc64le\":\n"
"    args.append(\"--enable-power\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4623
msgid ""
"Possible values for the ``family`` attribute are displayed by ``spack arch --"
"known-targets`` under the \"Generic architectures (families)\" header. "
"Finally it's possible to perform actions based on whether the current "
"microarchitecture is compatible with a known one:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4628
msgid ""
"if spec.target > \"haswell\":\n"
"    args.append(\"--needs-at-least-haswell\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4633
msgid ""
"The snippet above will add an item to a list of configure options only if "
"the current architecture is a superset of ``haswell`` or, said otherwise, "
"only if the current architecture is a later microarchitecture still "
"compatible with ``haswell``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4637
msgid "Using Spack on unknown microarchitectures"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4639
msgid ""
"If Spack is used on an unknown microarchitecture it will try to perform a "
"best match of the features it detects and will select the closest "
"microarchitecture it has information for. In case nothing matches, it will "
"create on the fly a new generic architecture. This is done to allow users to "
"still be able to use Spack for their work. The software built won't be "
"probably as optimized as it could but just as you need a newer compiler to "
"build for newer architectures, you may need newer versions of Spack for new "
"architectures to be correctly labeled."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4649
msgid "Accessing Dependencies"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4651
msgid ""
"You may need to get at some file or binary that's in the installation prefix "
"of one of your dependencies. You can do that by sub-scripting the spec:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4655
msgid "spec[\"mpi\"]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4659
msgid ""
"The value in the brackets needs to be some package name, and spec needs to "
"depend on that package, or the operation will fail.  For example, the above "
"code will fail if the ``spec`` doesn't depend on ``mpi``.  The value "
"returned is itself just another ``Spec`` object, so you can do all the same "
"things you would do with the package's own spec:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4666
msgid ""
"spec[\"mpi\"].prefix.bin\n"
"spec[\"mpi\"].version"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4675
msgid "Multimethods and ``@when``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4677
msgid ""
"Spack allows you to make multiple versions of instance functions in "
"packages, based on whether the package's spec satisfies particular criteria."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4681
msgid ""
"The ``@when`` annotation lets packages declare multiple versions of methods "
"like ``install()`` that depend on the package's spec.  For example:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4685
msgid ""
"class SomePackage(Package):\n"
"    ...\n"
"\n"
"    def install(self, prefix):\n"
"        # Do default install\n"
"\n"
"    @when(\"arch=chaos_5_x86_64_ib\")\n"
"    def install(self, prefix):\n"
"        # This will be executed instead of the default install if\n"
"        # the package's sys_type() is chaos_5_x86_64_ib.\n"
"\n"
"    @when(\"arch=linux-debian7-x86_64\")\n"
"    def install(self, prefix):\n"
"        # This will be executed if the package's sys_type() is\n"
"        # linux-debian7-x86_64."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4703
msgid ""
"In the above code there are three versions of ``install()``, two of which "
"are specialized for particular platforms.  The version that is called "
"depends on the architecture of the package spec."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4707
msgid ""
"Note that this works for methods other than install, as well.  So, if you "
"only have part of the install that is platform specific, you could do "
"something more like this:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4711
msgid ""
"class SomePackage(Package):\n"
"   ...\n"
"    # virtual dependence on MPI.\n"
"    # could resolve to mpich, mpich2, OpenMPI\n"
"    depends_on(\"mpi\")\n"
"\n"
"    def setup(self):\n"
"        # do nothing in the default case\n"
"        pass\n"
"\n"
"    @when(\"^openmpi\")\n"
"    def setup(self):\n"
"        # do something special when this is built with OpenMPI for\n"
"        # its MPI implementations.\n"
"\n"
"    def install(self, prefix):\n"
"        # Do common install stuff\n"
"        self.setup()\n"
"        # Do more common install stuff"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4733
msgid ""
"You can write multiple ``@when`` specs that satisfy the package's spec, for "
"example:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4736
msgid ""
"class SomePackage(Package):\n"
"    ...\n"
"    depends_on(\"mpi\")\n"
"\n"
"    def setup_mpi(self):\n"
"        # the default, called when no @when specs match\n"
"        pass\n"
"\n"
"    @when(\"^mpi@3:\")\n"
"    def setup_mpi(self):\n"
"        # this will be called when mpi is version 3 or higher\n"
"        pass\n"
"\n"
"    @when(\"^mpi@2:\")\n"
"    def setup_mpi(self):\n"
"        # this will be called when mpi is version 2 or higher\n"
"        pass\n"
"\n"
"    @when(\"^mpi@1:\")\n"
"    def setup_mpi(self):\n"
"        # this will be called when mpi is version 1 or higher\n"
"        pass"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4761
msgid ""
"In situations like this, the first matching spec, in declaration order will "
"be called.  As before, if no ``@when`` spec matches, the default method (the "
"one without the ``@when`` decorator) will be called."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4767
msgid ""
"The default version of decorated methods must **always** come first.  "
"Otherwise it will override all of the platform-specific versions.  There's "
"not much we can do to get around this because of the way decorators work."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4776
msgid "Compiler wrappers"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4778
msgid ""
"As mentioned, ``CC``, ``CXX``, ``F77``, and ``FC`` are set to point to "
"Spack's compiler wrappers.  These are simply called ``cc``, ``c++``, "
"``f77``, and ``f90``, and they live in ``$SPACK_ROOT/lib/spack/env``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4782
msgid ""
"``$SPACK_ROOT/lib/spack/env`` is added first in the ``PATH`` environment "
"variable when ``install()`` runs so that system compilers are not picked up "
"instead."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4786
msgid ""
"All of these compiler wrappers point to a single compiler wrapper script "
"that figures out which *real* compiler it should be building with.  This "
"comes either from spec `concretization <abstract-and-concrete>`_ or from a "
"user explicitly asking for a particular compiler using, e.g., ``%intel`` on "
"the command line."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4792
msgid ""
"In addition to invoking the right compiler, the compiler wrappers add flags "
"to the compile line so that dependencies can be easily found. These flags "
"are added for each dependency, if they exist:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4796
msgid ""
"Compile-time library search paths: ``-L$dep_prefix/lib``, ``-L$dep_prefix/"
"lib64``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4797
msgid ""
"Runtime library search paths (RPATHs): ``$rpath_flag$dep_prefix/lib``, "
"``$rpath_flag$dep_prefix/lib64``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4798
msgid "Include search paths: ``-I$dep_prefix/include``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4800
msgid ""
"An example of this would be the ``libdwarf`` build, which has one "
"dependency: ``libelf``.  Every call to ``cc`` in the ``libdwarf`` build will "
"have ``-I$LIBELF_PREFIX/include``, ``-L$LIBELF_PREFIX/lib``, and "
"``$rpath_flag$LIBELF_PREFIX/lib`` inserted on the command line.  This is "
"done transparently to the project's build system, which will just think it's "
"using a system where ``libelf`` is readily available.  Because of this, you "
"**do not** have to insert extra ``-I``, ``-L``, etc. on the command line."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4809
msgid ""
"Another useful consequence of this is that you often do *not* have to add "
"extra parameters on the ``configure`` line to get autotools to find "
"dependencies.  The ``libdwarf`` install method just calls configure like "
"this:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4814
msgid "configure(\"--prefix=\" + prefix)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4818
msgid ""
"Because of the ``-L`` and ``-I`` arguments, configure will successfully find "
"``libdwarf.h`` and ``libdwarf.so``, without the packager having to provide "
"``--with-libdwarf=/path/to/libdwarf`` on the command line."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4825
msgid ""
"For most compilers, ``$rpath_flag`` is ``-Wl,-rpath,``. However, NAG passes "
"its flags to GCC instead of passing them directly to the linker. Therefore, "
"its ``$rpath_flag`` is doubly wrapped: ``-Wl,-Wl,,-rpath,``. ``$rpath_flag`` "
"can be overridden on a compiler specific basis in ``lib/spack/spack/"
"compilers/$compiler.py``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4831
msgid ""
"The compiler wrappers also pass the compiler flags specified by the user "
"from the command line (``cflags``, ``cxxflags``, ``fflags``, ``cppflags``, "
"``ldflags``, and/or ``ldlibs``). They do not override the canonical "
"autotools flags with the same names (but in ALL-CAPS) that may be passed "
"into the build by particularly challenging package scripts."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4839
msgid "MPI support in Spack"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4841
msgid ""
"It is common for high performance computing software/packages to use the "
"Message Passing Interface ( ``MPI``).  As a result of conretization, a given "
"package can be built using different implementations of MPI such as "
"``Openmpi``, ``MPICH`` or ``IntelMPI``.  That is, when your package declares "
"that it ``depends_on(\"mpi\")``, it can be built with any of these ``mpi`` "
"implementations. In some scenarios, to configure a package, one has to "
"provide it with appropriate MPI compiler wrappers such as ``mpicc``, ``mpic+"
"+``.  However different implementations of ``MPI`` may have different names "
"for those wrappers."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4851
msgid ""
"Spack provides an idiomatic way to use MPI compilers in your package.  To "
"use MPI wrappers to compile your whole build, do this in your ``install()`` "
"method:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4855 ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4913
msgid ""
"env[\"CC\"] = spec[\"mpi\"].mpicc\n"
"env[\"CXX\"] = spec[\"mpi\"].mpicxx\n"
"env[\"F77\"] = spec[\"mpi\"].mpif77\n"
"env[\"FC\"] = spec[\"mpi\"].mpifc"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4862
msgid "That's all.  A longer explanation of why this works is below."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4864
msgid ""
"We don't try to force any particular build method on packagers.  The "
"decision to use MPI wrappers depends on the way the package is written, on "
"common practice, and on \"what works\".  Loosely, There are three types of "
"MPI builds:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4869
msgid ""
"Some build systems work well without the wrappers and can treat MPI as an "
"external library, where the person doing the build has to supply includes/"
"libs/etc.  This is fairly uncommon."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4873
msgid ""
"Others really want the wrappers and assume you're using an MPI \"compiler\" "
"– i.e., they have no mechanism to add MPI includes/libraries/etc."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4877
msgid ""
"CMake's ``FindMPI`` needs the compiler wrappers, but it uses them to extract "
"``–I`` / ``-L`` / ``-D`` arguments, then treats MPI like a regular library."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4881
msgid ""
"Note that some CMake builds fall into case 2 because they either don't know "
"about or don't like CMake's ``FindMPI`` support – they just assume an MPI "
"compiler. Also, some autotools builds fall into case 3 (e.g. `here is an "
"autotools version of CMake's FindMPI <https://github.com/tgamblin/libra/blob/"
"master/m4/lx_find_mpi.m4>`_)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4887
msgid ""
"Given all of this, we leave the use of the wrappers up to the packager. "
"Spack will support all three ways of building MPI packages."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4892
msgid "Packaging Conventions"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4894
msgid ""
"As mentioned above, in the ``install()`` method, ``CC``, ``CXX``, ``F77``, "
"and ``FC`` point to Spack's wrappers around the chosen compiler. Spack's "
"wrappers are not the MPI compiler wrappers, though they do automatically add "
"``–I``, ``–L``, and ``–Wl,-rpath`` args for dependencies in a similar way.  "
"The MPI wrappers are a bit different in that they also add ``-l`` arguments "
"for the MPI libraries, and some add special ``-D`` arguments to trigger "
"build options in MPI programs."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4902
msgid ""
"For case 1 above, you generally don't need to do more than patch your "
"Makefile or add configure args as you normally would."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4905
msgid ""
"For case 3, you don't need to do much of anything, as Spack puts the MPI "
"compiler wrappers in the PATH, and the build will find them and interrogate "
"them."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4909
msgid ""
"For case 2, things are a bit more complicated, as you'll need to tell the "
"build to use the MPI compiler wrappers instead of Spack's compiler "
"wrappers.  All it takes some lines like this:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4920
msgid ""
"Or, if you pass CC, CXX, etc. directly to your build with, e.g., `--with-"
"cc=<path>`, you'll want to substitute `spec[\"mpi\"].mpicc` in there "
"instead, e.g.:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4924
msgid ""
"configure(\"—prefix=%s\" % prefix,\n"
"          \"—with-cc=%s\" % spec[\"mpi\"].mpicc)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4929
msgid ""
"Now, you may think that doing this will lose the includes, library paths, "
"and RPATHs that Spack's compiler wrapper get you, but we've actually set "
"things up so that the MPI compiler wrappers use Spack's compiler wrappers "
"when run from within Spack. So using the MPI wrappers should really be as "
"simple as the code above."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4937
msgid "``spec[\"mpi\"]``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4939
msgid "Ok, so how does all this work?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4941
msgid ""
"If your package has a virtual dependency like ``mpi``, then referring to "
"``spec[\"mpi\"]`` within ``install()`` will get you the concrete ``mpi`` "
"implementation in your dependency DAG.  That is a spec object just like the "
"one passed to install, only the MPI implementations all set some additional "
"properties on it to help you out.  E.g., in mvapich2, you'll find this:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4948
msgid ""
"    def setup_dependent_package(self, module, dependent_spec):\n"
"        self.spec.mpicc = join_path(self.prefix.bin, \"mpicc\")\n"
"        self.spec.mpicxx = join_path(self.prefix.bin, \"mpicxx\")\n"
"        self.spec.mpifc = join_path(self.prefix.bin, \"mpif90\")\n"
"        self.spec.mpif77 = join_path(self.prefix.bin, \"mpif77\")\n"
"        self.spec.mpicxx_shared_libs = [\n"
"            os.path.join(self.prefix.lib, \"libmpicxx.{0}\"."
"format(dso_suffix)),\n"
"            os.path.join(self.prefix.lib, \"libmpi.{0}\"."
"format(dso_suffix)),\n"
"        ]\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4951
msgid ""
"That code allows the mvapich2 package to associate an ``mpicc`` property "
"with the ``mvapich2`` node in the DAG, so that dependents can access it. "
"``openmpi`` and ``mpich`` do similar things.  So, no matter what MPI you're "
"using, spec[\"mpi\"].mpicc gets you the location of the MPI compilers. This "
"allows us to have a fairly simple polymorphic interface for information "
"about virtual dependencies like MPI."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4960
msgid "Wrapping wrappers"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4962
msgid ""
"Spack likes to use its own compiler wrappers to make it easy to add "
"``RPATHs`` to builds, and to try hard to ensure that your builds use the "
"right dependencies.  This doesn't play nicely by default with MPI, so we "
"have to do a couple tricks."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4967
msgid ""
"If we build MPI with Spack's wrappers, mpicc and friends will be installed "
"with hard-coded paths to Spack's wrappers, and using them from outside of "
"Spack will fail because they only work within Spack. To fix this, we patch "
"mpicc and friends to use the regular compilers.  Look at the "
"filter_compilers method in mpich, openmpi, or mvapich2 for details."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4974
msgid ""
"We still want to use the Spack compiler wrappers when Spack is calling "
"mpicc. Luckily, wrappers in all mainstream MPI implementations provide "
"environment variables that allow us to dynamically set the compiler to be "
"used by mpicc, mpicxx, etc. Denis pasted some code from this below – Spack's "
"build environment sets ``MPICC``, ``MPICXX``, etc. for mpich derivatives and "
"``OMPI_CC``, ``OMPI_CXX``, etc. for OpenMPI. This makes the MPI compiler "
"wrappers use the Spack compiler wrappers so that your dependencies still get "
"proper RPATHs even if you use the MPI wrappers."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4987
msgid "MPI on Cray machines"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4989
msgid ""
"The Cray programming environment notably uses ITS OWN compiler wrappers, "
"which function like MPI wrappers.  On Cray systems, the ``CC``, ``cc``, and "
"``ftn`` wrappers ARE the MPI compiler wrappers, and it's assumed that you'll "
"use them for all of your builds.  So on Cray we don't bother with ``mpicc``, "
"``mpicxx``, etc, Spack MPI implementations set ``spec[\"mpi\"].mpicc`` to "
"point to Spack's wrappers, which wrap the Cray wrappers, which wrap the "
"regular compilers and include MPI flags.  That may seem complicated, but for "
"packagers, that means the same code for using MPI wrappers will work, even "
"on even on a Cray:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:4999
msgid "env[\"CC\"] = spec[\"mpi\"].mpicc"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:5003
msgid "This is because on Cray, ``spec[\"mpi\"].mpicc`` is just ``spack_cc``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:5009
msgid "Checking an installation"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:5011
msgid ""
"A package that *appears* to install successfully does not mean it is "
"actually installed correctly or will continue to work indefinitely. There "
"are a number of possible points of failure so Spack provides features for "
"checking the software along the way."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:5016
msgid ""
"Failures can occur during and after the installation process. The build may "
"start but the software not end up fully installed. The installed software "
"may not work at all or as expected. The software may work after being "
"installed but, due to changes on the system, may stop working days, weeks, "
"or months after being installed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:5022
msgid ""
"This section describes Spack's support for checks that can be performed "
"during and after its installation. The former checks are referred to as "
"``build-time tests`` and the latter as ``stand-alone (or smoke) tests``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:5030
msgid "Build-time tests"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:5032
msgid ""
"Spack infers the status of a build based on the contents of the install "
"prefix. Success is assumed if anything (e.g., a file, directory) is written "
"after ``install()`` completes. Otherwise, the build is assumed to have "
"failed. However, the presence of install prefix contents is not a sufficient "
"indicator of success so Spack supports the addition of tests that can be "
"performed during `spack install` processing."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:5039
msgid "Consider a simple autotools build using the following commands:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:5041
msgid ""
"$ ./configure --prefix=/path/to/installation/prefix\n"
"$ make\n"
"$ make install"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:5047
msgid ""
"Standard Autotools and CMake do not write anything to the prefix from the "
"``configure`` and ``make`` commands. Files are only written from the ``make "
"install`` after the build completes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:5053
msgid ""
"If you want to learn more about ``Autotools`` and ``CMake`` packages in "
"Spack, refer to :ref:`AutotoolsPackage <autotoolspackage>` and :ref:"
"`CMakePackage <cmakepackage>`, respectively."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:5057
msgid ""
"What can you do to check that the build is progressing satisfactorily? If "
"there are specific files and or directories expected of a successful "
"installation, you can add basic, fast ``sanity checks``. You can also add "
"checks to be performed after one or more installation phases."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:5064
msgid ""
"Build-time tests are performed when the ``--test`` option is passed to "
"``spack install``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:5069
msgid ""
"Build-time test failures result in a failed installation of the software."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:5076
msgid "Adding sanity checks"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:5078
msgid ""
"Unfortunately, many builds of scientific software modify the installation "
"prefix **before** ``make install``. Builds like this can falsely report "
"success when an error occurs before the installation is complete. Simple "
"sanity checks can be used to identify files and or directories that are "
"required of a successful installation. Spack checks for the presence of the "
"files and directories after ``install()`` runs."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:5085
msgid ""
"If any of the listed files or directories are missing, then the build will "
"fail and the install prefix will be removed. If they all exist, then Spack "
"considers the build successful from a sanity check perspective and keeps the "
"prefix in place."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:5090
msgid ""
"For example, the sanity checks for the ``reframe`` package below specify "
"that eight paths must exist within the installation prefix after the "
"``install`` method completes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:5094
msgid ""
"class Reframe(Package):\n"
"    ...\n"
"\n"
"    # sanity check\n"
"    sanity_check_is_file = [join_path(\"bin\", \"reframe\")]\n"
"    sanity_check_is_dir  = [\"bin\", \"config\", \"docs\", \"reframe\", "
"\"tutorials\",\n"
"                            \"unittests\", \"cscs-checks\"]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:5104
msgid ""
"When you run ``spack install`` with tests enabled, Spack will ensure that a "
"successfully installed package has the required files and or directories."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:5107
msgid "For example, running:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:5109
msgid "$ spack install --test=root reframe"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:5113
msgid ""
"results in spack checking that the installation created the following "
"**file**:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:5115
msgid "``self.prefix.bin.reframe``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:5117
msgid "and the following **directories**:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:5119
msgid "``self.prefix.bin``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:5120
msgid "``self.prefix.config``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:5121
msgid "``self.prefix.docs``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:5122
msgid "``self.prefix.reframe``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:5123
msgid "``self.prefix.tutorials``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:5124
msgid "``self.prefix.unittests``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:5125
msgid "``self.prefix.cscs-checks``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:5127
msgid ""
"If **any** of these paths are missing, then Spack considers the installation "
"to have failed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:5132
msgid ""
"You **MUST** use ``sanity_check_is_file`` to specify required files and "
"``sanity_check_is_dir`` for required directories."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:5139
msgid "Adding installation phase tests"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:5141
msgid ""
"Sometimes packages appear to build \"correctly\" only to have run-time "
"behavior issues discovered at a later stage, such as after a full software "
"stack relying on them has been built. Checks can be performed at different "
"phases of the package installation to possibly avoid these types of "
"problems. Some checks are built-in to different build systems, while others "
"will need to be added to the package."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:5148
msgid ""
"Built-in installation phase tests are provided by packages inheriting from "
"select :ref:`build systems <build-systems>`, where naming conventions are "
"used to identify typical test identifiers for those systems. In general, you "
"won't need to add anything to your package to take advantage of these tests "
"if your software's build system complies with the convention; otherwise, "
"you'll want or need to override the post-phase method to perform other "
"checks."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:5156
msgid "Built-in installation phase tests"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:5159
msgid "Build System Class"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:5160
msgid "Post-Build Phase Method (Runs)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:5161
msgid "Post-Install Phase Method (Runs)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:5162
msgid ":ref:`AutotoolsPackage <autotoolspackage>`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:5163 ../../../packaging_guide.rst:5172
#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:5175
msgid "``check`` (``make test``, ``make check``)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:5164 ../../../packaging_guide.rst:5173
msgid "``installcheck`` (``make installcheck``)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:5165
msgid ":ref:`CachedCMakePackage <cachedcmakepackage>`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:5166 ../../../packaging_guide.rst:5169
msgid "``check`` (``make check``, ``make test``)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:5167 ../../../packaging_guide.rst:5170
#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:5176 ../../../packaging_guide.rst:5179
#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:5181 ../../../packaging_guide.rst:5185
#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:5188 ../../../packaging_guide.rst:5190
msgid "Not applicable"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:5168
msgid ":ref:`CMakePackage <cmakepackage>`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:5171
msgid ":ref:`MakefilePackage <makefilepackage>`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:5174
msgid ":ref:`MesonPackage <mesonpackage>`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:5177
msgid ":ref:`PerlPackage <perlpackage>`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:5178
msgid "``check`` (``make test``)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:5180 ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6059
msgid ":ref:`PythonPackage <pythonpackage>`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:5182 ../../../packaging_guide.rst:5191
msgid "``test`` (module imports)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:5183
msgid ":ref:`QMakePackage <qmakepackage>`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:5184
msgid "``check`` (``make check``)"
msgstr ""

