#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6123
msgid "``spack test list``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6125
msgid ""
"Packages available for install testing can be found using the ``spack test "
"list`` command. The command outputs all installed packages that have defined "
"stand-alone test methods."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6129
msgid ""
"Alternatively you can use the ``--all`` option to get a list of all packages "
"that have stand-alone test methods even if the packages are not installed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6133
msgid ""
"For more information, refer to `spack test list <https://spack.readthedocs."
"io/en/latest/command_index.html#spack-test-list>`_."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6140
msgid "``spack test run``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6142
msgid ""
"Install tests can be run for one or more installed packages using the "
"``spack test run`` command. A ``test suite`` is created for all of the "
"provided specs. The command accepts the same arguments provided to ``spack "
"install`` (see :ref:`sec-specs`). If no specs are provided the command tests "
"all specs in the active environment or all specs installed in the Spack "
"instance if no environment is active."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6149
msgid ""
"Test suites can be named using the ``--alias`` option. Unaliased test suites "
"use the content hash of their specs as their name."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6152
msgid "Some of the more commonly used debugging options are:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6154
msgid "``--fail-fast`` stops testing each package after the first failure"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6155
msgid "``--fail-first`` stops testing packages after the first failure"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6157
msgid ""
"Test output is written to a text log file by default though ``junit`` and "
"``cdash`` are outputs available through the ``--log-format`` option."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6160
msgid ""
"For more information, refer to `spack test run <https://spack.readthedocs.io/"
"en/latest/command_index.html#spack-test-run>`_."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6168
msgid "``spack test results``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6170
msgid ""
"The ``spack test results`` command shows results for all completed test "
"suites by default. The alias or content hash can be provided to limit "
"reporting to the corresponding test suite."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6174
msgid ""
"The ``--logs`` option includes the output generated by the associated "
"test(s) to facilitate debugging."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6177
msgid ""
"The ``--failed`` option limits results shown to that of the failed tests, if "
"any, of matching packages."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6180
msgid ""
"For more information, refer to `spack test results <https://spack."
"readthedocs.io/en/latest/command_index.html#spack-test-results>`_."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6187
msgid "``spack test find``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6189
msgid ""
"The ``spack test find`` command lists the aliases or content hashes of all "
"test suites whose results are available."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6192
msgid ""
"For more information, refer to `spack test find <https://spack.readthedocs."
"io/en/latest/command_index.html#spack-test-find>`_."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6199
msgid "``spack test remove``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6201
msgid ""
"The ``spack test remove`` command removes test suites to declutter the test "
"stage directory. You are prompted to confirm the removal of each test suite "
"**unless** you use the ``--yes-to-all`` option."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6205
msgid ""
"For more information, refer to `spack test remove <https://spack.readthedocs."
"io/en/latest/command_index.html#spack-test-remove>`_."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6213
msgid "File manipulation functions"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6215
msgid ""
"Many builds are not perfect. If a build lacks an install target, or if it "
"does not use systems like CMake or autotools, which have standard ways of "
"setting compilers and options, you may need to edit files or install some "
"files yourself to get them working with Spack."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6220
msgid ""
"You can do this with standard Python code, and Python has rich libraries "
"with functions for file manipulation and filtering. Spack also provides a "
"number of convenience functions of its own to make your life even easier. "
"These functions are described in this section."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6225
msgid "All of the functions in this section can be included by simply running:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6228
msgid "from spack import *"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6232
msgid ""
"This is already part of the boilerplate for packages created with ``spack "
"create``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6239
msgid "Filtering functions"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6241
msgid ""
":py:func:`filter_file(regex, repl, *filenames, **kwargs) <llnl.util."
"filesystem.filter_file>`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6242
msgid ""
"Works like ``sed`` but with Python regular expression syntax.  Takes a "
"regular expression, a replacement, and a set of files.  ``repl`` can be a "
"raw string or a callable function.  If it is a raw string, it can contain "
"``\\1``, ``\\2``, etc. to refer to capture groups in the regular "
"expression.  If it is a callable, it is passed the Python ``MatchObject`` "
"and should return a suitable replacement string for the particular match."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6250
msgid "Examples:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6252
msgid "Filtering a Makefile to force it to use Spack's compiler wrappers:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6254
msgid ""
"filter_file(r\"^\\s*CC\\s*=.*\",  \"CC = \"  + spack_cc,  \"Makefile\")\n"
"filter_file(r\"^\\s*CXX\\s*=.*\", \"CXX = \" + spack_cxx, \"Makefile\")\n"
"filter_file(r\"^\\s*F77\\s*=.*\", \"F77 = \" + spack_f77, \"Makefile\")\n"
"filter_file(r\"^\\s*FC\\s*=.*\",  \"FC = \"  + spack_fc,  \"Makefile\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6261
msgid ""
"Replacing ``#!/usr/bin/perl`` with ``#!/usr/bin/env perl`` in ``bib2xhtml``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6263
msgid ""
"filter_file(r\"#!/usr/bin/perl\",\n"
"            \"#!/usr/bin/env perl\", prefix.bin.bib2xhtml)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6268
msgid ""
"Switching the compilers used by ``mpich``'s MPI wrapper scripts from ``cc``, "
"etc. to the compilers used by the Spack build:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6271
msgid ""
"filter_file(\"CC='cc'\", \"CC='%s'\" % self.compiler.cc,\n"
"            prefix.bin.mpicc)\n"
"\n"
"filter_file(\"CXX='c++'\", \"CXX='%s'\" % self.compiler.cxx,\n"
"            prefix.bin.mpicxx)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6279
msgid ""
":py:func:`change_sed_delimiter(old_delim, new_delim, *filenames) <llnl.util."
"filesystem.change_sed_delimiter>`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6280
msgid ""
"Some packages, like TAU, have a build system that can't install into "
"directories with, e.g. \"@\" in the name, because they use hard-coded "
"``sed`` commands in their build."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6284
msgid ""
"``change_sed_delimiter`` finds all ``sed`` search/replace commands and "
"change the delimiter.  e.g., if the file contains commands that look like "
"``s///``, you can use this to change them to ``s@@@``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6289
msgid "Example of changing ``s///`` to ``s@@@`` in TAU:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6291
msgid ""
"change_sed_delimiter(\"@\", \";\", \"configure\")\n"
"change_sed_delimiter(\"@\", \";\", \"utils/FixMakefile\")\n"
"change_sed_delimiter(\"@\", \";\", \"utils/FixMakefile.sed.default\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6299
msgid "File functions"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6301
msgid ":py:func:`ancestor(dir, n=1) <llnl.util.filesystem.ancestor>`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6302
msgid "Get the n\\ :sup:`th` ancestor of the directory ``dir``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6304
msgid ":py:func:`can_access(path) <llnl.util.filesystem.can_access>`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6305
msgid ""
"True if we can read and write to the file at ``path``.  Same as native "
"python ``os.access(file_name, os.R_OK|os.W_OK)``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6308
msgid ":py:func:`install(src, dest) <llnl.util.filesystem.install>`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6309
msgid ""
"Install a file to a particular location.  For example, install a header into "
"the ``include`` directory under the install ``prefix``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6312
msgid "install(\"my-header.h\", prefix.include)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6316
msgid ":py:func:`join_path(*paths) <llnl.util.filesystem.join_path>`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6317
msgid ""
"An alias for ``os.path.join``. This joins paths using the OS path separator."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6319
msgid ":py:func:`mkdirp(*paths) <llnl.util.filesystem.mkdirp>`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6320
msgid ""
"Create each of the directories in ``paths``, creating any parent directories "
"if they do not exist."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6323
msgid ""
":py:func:`working_dir(dirname, kwargs) <llnl.util.filesystem.working_dir>`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6324
msgid ""
"This is a Python `Context Manager <https://docs.python.org/2/library/"
"contextlib.html>`_ that makes it easier to work with subdirectories in "
"builds.  You use this with the Python ``with`` statement to change into a "
"working directory, and when the with block is done, you change back to the "
"original directory.  Think of it as a safe ``pushd`` / ``popd`` combination, "
"where ``popd`` is guaranteed to be called at the end, even if exceptions are "
"thrown."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6333
msgid "Example usage:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6335
msgid ""
"The ``libdwarf`` build first runs ``configure`` and ``make`` in a "
"subdirectory called ``libdwarf``.  It then implements the installation code "
"itself.  This is natural with ``working_dir``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6339
msgid ""
"with working_dir(\"libdwarf\"):\n"
"    configure(\"--prefix=\" + prefix, \"--enable-shared\")\n"
"    make()\n"
"    install(\"libdwarf.a\",  prefix.lib)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6346
msgid ""
"Many CMake builds require that you build \"out of source\", that is, in a "
"subdirectory.  You can handle creating and ``cd``'ing to the subdirectory "
"like the LLVM package does:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6350
msgid ""
"with working_dir(\"spack-build\", create=True):\n"
"    cmake(\"..\",\n"
"          \"-DLLVM_REQUIRES_RTTI=1\",\n"
"          \"-DPYTHON_EXECUTABLE=/usr/bin/python\",\n"
"          \"-DPYTHON_INCLUDE_DIR=/usr/include/python2.6\",\n"
"          \"-DPYTHON_LIBRARY=/usr/lib64/libpython2.6.so\",\n"
"          *std_cmake_args)\n"
"    make()\n"
"    make(\"install\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6362
msgid ""
"The ``create=True`` keyword argument causes the command to create the "
"directory if it does not exist."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6365
msgid ":py:func:`touch(path) <llnl.util.filesystem.touch>`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6366
msgid "Create an empty file at ``path``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6372
msgid "Making a package discoverable with ``spack external find``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6374
msgid ""
"The simplest way to make a package discoverable with :ref:`spack external "
"find <cmd-spack-external-find>` is to:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6377
msgid "Define the executables associated with the package"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6378
msgid "Implement a method to determine the versions of these executables"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6382
msgid "Minimal detection"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6384
msgid ""
"The first step is fairly simple, as it requires only to specify a package "
"level ``executables`` attribute:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6387
msgid ""
"class Foo(Package):\n"
"    # Each string provided here is treated as a regular expression, and\n"
"    # would match for example \"foo\", \"foobar\", and \"bazfoo\".\n"
"    executables = [\"foo\"]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6394
msgid ""
"This attribute must be a list of strings. Each string is a regular "
"expression (e.g. \"gcc\" would match \"gcc\", \"gcc-8.3\", \"my-weird-gcc\", "
"etc.) to determine a set of system executables that might be part or this "
"package. Note that to match only executables named \"gcc\" the regular "
"expression ``\"^gcc$\"`` must be used."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6400
msgid ""
"Finally to determine the version of each executable the "
"``determine_version`` method must be implemented:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6403
msgid ""
"@classmethod\n"
"def determine_version(cls, exe):\n"
"    \"\"\"Return either the version of the executable passed as argument\n"
"    or ``None`` if the version cannot be determined.\n"
"\n"
"    Args:\n"
"        exe (str): absolute path to the executable being examined\n"
"    \"\"\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6414
msgid ""
"This method receives as input the path to a single executable and must "
"return as output its version as a string; if the user cannot determine the "
"version or determines that the executable is not an instance of the package, "
"they can return None and the exe will be discarded as a candidate. "
"Implementing the two steps above is mandatory, and gives the package the "
"basic ability to detect if a spec is present on the system at a given "
"version."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6422
msgid ""
"Any executable for which the ``determine_version`` method returns ``None`` "
"will be discarded and won't appear in later stages of the workflow described "
"below."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6427
msgid "Additional functionality"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6429
msgid ""
"Besides the two mandatory steps described above, there are also optional "
"methods that can be implemented to either increase the amount of details "
"being detected or improve the robustness of the detection logic in a package."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6435
msgid "Variants and custom attributes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6437
msgid ""
"The ``determine_variants`` method can be optionally implemented in a package "
"to detect additional details of the spec:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6440
msgid ""
"@classmethod\n"
"def determine_variants(cls, exes, version_str):\n"
"    \"\"\"Return either a variant string, a tuple of a variant string\n"
"    and a dictionary of extra attributes that will be recorded in\n"
"    packages.yaml or a list of those items.\n"
"\n"
"    Args:\n"
"        exes (list of str): list of executables (absolute paths) that\n"
"            live in the same prefix and share the same version\n"
"        version_str (str): version associated with the list of\n"
"            executables, as detected by ``determine_version``\n"
"    \"\"\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6455
msgid ""
"This method takes as input a list of executables that live in the same "
"prefix and share the same version string, and returns either:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6458
msgid "A variant string"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6459
msgid "A tuple of a variant string and a dictionary of extra attributes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6460
msgid ""
"A list of items matching either 1 or 2 (if multiple specs are detected from "
"the set of executables)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6463
msgid ""
"If extra attributes are returned, they will be recorded in ``packages.yaml`` "
"and be available for later reuse. As an example, the ``gcc`` package will "
"record by default the different compilers found and an entry in ``packages."
"yaml`` would look like:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6468
msgid ""
"packages:\n"
"  gcc:\n"
"    externals:\n"
"    - spec: \"gcc@9.0.1 languages=c,c++,fortran\"\n"
"      prefix: /usr\n"
"      extra_attributes:\n"
"        compilers:\n"
"          c: /usr/bin/x86_64-linux-gnu-gcc-9\n"
"          c++: /usr/bin/x86_64-linux-gnu-g++-9\n"
"          fortran: /usr/bin/x86_64-linux-gnu-gfortran-9"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6481
msgid ""
"This allows us, for instance, to keep track of executables that would be "
"named differently if built by Spack (e.g. ``x86_64-linux-gnu-gcc-9`` instead "
"of just ``gcc``)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6492
msgid "Filter matching executables"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6494
msgid ""
"Sometimes defining the appropriate regex for the ``executables`` attribute "
"might prove to be difficult, especially if one has to deal with corner cases "
"or exclude \"red herrings\". To help keeping the regular expressions as "
"simple as possible, each package can optionally implement a "
"``filter_executables`` method:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6500
msgid ""
"@classmethod\n"
"def filter_detected_exes(cls, prefix, exes_in_prefix):\n"
"    \"\"\"Return a filtered list of the executables in prefix\"\"\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6506
msgid ""
"which takes as input a prefix and a list of matching executables and returns "
"a filtered list of said executables."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6509
msgid ""
"Using this method has the advantage of allowing custom logic for filtering, "
"and does not restrict the user to regular expressions only.  Consider the "
"case of detecting the GNU C++ compiler. If we try to search for executables "
"that match ``g++``, that would have the unwanted side effect of selecting "
"also ``clang++`` - which is a C++ compiler provided by another package - if "
"present on the system. Trying to select executables that contain ``g++`` but "
"not ``clang`` would be quite complicated to do using regex only. Employing "
"the ``filter_detected_exes`` method it becomes:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6519
msgid ""
"class Gcc(Package):\n"
"   executables = [\"g++\"]\n"
"\n"
"   def filter_detected_exes(cls, prefix, exes_in_prefix):\n"
"      return [x for x in exes_in_prefix if \"clang\" not in x]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6527
msgid ""
"Another possibility that this method opens is to apply certain filtering "
"logic when specific conditions are met (e.g. take some decisions on an OS "
"and not on another)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6533
msgid "Validate detection"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6535
msgid ""
"To increase detection robustness, packagers may also implement a method to "
"validate the detected Spec objects:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6538
msgid ""
"@classmethod\n"
"def validate_detected_spec(cls, spec, extra_attributes):\n"
"    \"\"\"Validate a detected spec. Raise an exception if validation fails."
"\"\"\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6544
msgid ""
"This method receives a detected spec along with its extra attributes and can "
"be used to check that certain conditions are met by the spec. Packagers can "
"either use assertions or raise an ``InvalidSpecDetected`` exception when the "
"check fails. In case the conditions are not honored the spec will be "
"discarded and any message associated with the assertion or the exception "
"will be logged as the reason for discarding it."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6551
msgid ""
"As an example, a package that wants to check that the ``compilers`` "
"attribute is in the extra attributes can implement this method like this:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6554
msgid ""
"@classmethod\n"
"def validate_detected_spec(cls, spec, extra_attributes):\n"
"    \"\"\"Check that \"compilers\" is in the extra attributes.\"\"\"\n"
"    msg = (\"the extra attribute 'compilers' must be set for \"\n"
"           \"the detected spec '{0}'\".format(spec))\n"
"    assert \"compilers\" in extra_attributes, msg"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6563
msgid "or like this:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6565
msgid ""
"@classmethod\n"
"def validate_detected_spec(cls, spec, extra_attributes):\n"
"    \"\"\"Check that \"compilers\" is in the extra attributes.\"\"\"\n"
"    if \"compilers\" not in extra_attributes:\n"
"        msg = (\"the extra attribute 'compilers' must be set for \"\n"
"               \"the detected spec '{0}'\".format(spec))\n"
"        raise InvalidSpecDetected(msg)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6579
msgid "Custom detection workflow"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6581
msgid ""
"In the rare case when the mechanisms described so far don't fit the "
"detection of a package, the implementation of all the methods above can be "
"disregarded and instead a custom ``determine_spec_details`` method can be "
"implemented directly in the package class (note that the definition of the "
"``executables`` attribute is still required):"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6587
msgid ""
"@classmethod\n"
"def determine_spec_details(cls, prefix, exes_in_prefix):\n"
"    # exes_in_prefix = a set of paths, each path is an executable\n"
"    # prefix = a prefix that is common to each path in exes_in_prefix\n"
"\n"
"    # return None or [] if none of the exes represent an instance of\n"
"    # the package. Return one or more Specs for each instance of the\n"
"    # package which is thought to be installed in the provided prefix"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6598
msgid ""
"This method takes as input a set of discovered executables (which match "
"those specified by the user) as well as a common prefix shared by all of "
"those executables. The function must return one or more :py:class:`spack."
"spec.Spec` associated with the executables (it can also return ``None`` to "
"indicate that no provided executables are associated with the package)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6604
msgid ""
"As an example, consider a made-up package called ``foo-package`` which "
"builds an executable called ``foo``. ``FooPackage`` would appear as follows:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6608
msgid ""
"class FooPackage(Package):\n"
"    homepage = \"...\"\n"
"    url = \"...\"\n"
"\n"
"    version(...)\n"
"\n"
"    # Each string provided here is treated as a regular expression, and\n"
"    # would match for example \"foo\", \"foobar\", and \"bazfoo\".\n"
"    executables = [\"foo\"]\n"
"\n"
"    @classmethod\n"
"    def determine_spec_details(cls, prefix, exes_in_prefix):\n"
"        candidates = list(x for x in exes_in_prefix\n"
"                          if os.path.basename(x) == \"foo\")\n"
"        if not candidates:\n"
"            return\n"
"        # This implementation is lazy and only checks the first candidate\n"
"        exe_path = candidates[0]\n"
"        exe = Executable(exe_path)\n"
"        output = exe(\"--version\", output=str, error=str)\n"
"        version_str = ...  # parse output for version string\n"
"        return Spec.from_detection(\n"
"            \"foo-package@{0}\".format(version_str)\n"
"        )"
msgstr ""

