msgid ""
"If specified in this table, the corresponding default should be used when "
"declaring a variant."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6763
msgid ""
"The semantics of the `shared` variant are important. When a package is built "
"`~shared`, the package guarantees that no shared libraries are built. When a "
"package is built `+shared`, the package guarantees that shared libraries are "
"built, but it makes no guarantee about whether static libraries are built."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6771
msgid "Version Lists"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6773
msgid "Spack packages should list supported versions with the newest first."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6777
msgid "Using ``home`` vs ``prefix``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6779
msgid ""
"``home`` and ``prefix`` are both attributes that can be queried on a "
"package's dependencies, often when passing configure arguments pointing to "
"the location of a dependency.  The difference is that while ``prefix`` is "
"the location on disk where a concrete package resides, ``home`` is the "
"`logical` location that a package resides, which may be different than "
"``prefix`` in the case of virtual packages or other special circumstances.  "
"For most use cases inside a package, its dependency locations can be "
"accessed via either ``self.spec[\"foo\"].home`` or ``self.spec[\"foo\"]."
"prefix``.  Specific packages that should be consumed by dependents via ``."
"home`` instead of ``.prefix`` should be noted in their respective "
"documentation."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6790
msgid ""
"See :ref:`custom-attributes` for more details and an example implementing a "
"custom ``home`` attribute."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6795
msgid "Packaging workflow commands"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6797
msgid ""
"When you are building packages, you will likely not get things completely "
"right the first time."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6800
msgid ""
"The ``spack install`` command performs a number of tasks before it finally "
"installs each package.  It downloads an archive, expands it in a temporary "
"directory, and only then gives control to the package's ``install()`` "
"method.  If the build doesn't go as planned, you may want to clean up the "
"temporary directory, or if the package isn't downloading properly, you might "
"want to run *only* the ``fetch`` stage of the build."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6808
msgid ""
"Spack performs best-effort installation of package dependencies by default, "
"which means it will continue to install as many dependencies as possible "
"after detecting failures.  If you are trying to install a package with a lot "
"of dependencies where one or more may fail to build, you might want to try "
"the ``--fail-fast`` option to stop the installation process on the first "
"failure."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6815
msgid "A typical package workflow might look like this:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6817
msgid ""
"$ spack edit mypackage\n"
"$ spack install --fail-fast mypackage\n"
"... build breaks! ...\n"
"$ spack clean mypackage\n"
"$ spack edit mypackage\n"
"$ spack install --fail-fast mypackage\n"
"... repeat clean/install until install works ..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6827
msgid ""
"Below are some commands that will allow you some finer-grained control over "
"the install process."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6834
msgid "``spack fetch``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6836
msgid ""
"The first step of ``spack install``.  Takes a spec and determines the "
"correct download URL to use for the requested package version, then "
"downloads the archive, checks it against an MD5 checksum, and stores it in a "
"staging directory if the check was successful.  The staging directory will "
"be located under the first writable directory in the ``build_stage`` "
"configuration setting."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6843
msgid ""
"When run after the archive has already been downloaded, ``spack fetch`` is "
"idempotent and will not download the archive again."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6850
msgid "``spack stage``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6852
msgid ""
"The second step in ``spack install`` after ``spack fetch``.  Expands the "
"downloaded archive in its temporary directory, where it will be built by "
"``spack install``.  Similar to ``fetch``, if the archive has already been "
"expanded,  ``stage`` is idempotent."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6861
msgid "``spack patch``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6863
msgid ""
"After staging, Spack applies patches to downloaded packages, if any have "
"been specified in the package file.  This command will run the install "
"process through the fetch, stage, and patch phases.  Spack keeps track of "
"whether patches have already been applied and skips this step if they have "
"been.  If Spack discovers that patches didn't apply cleanly on some previous "
"run, then it will restage the entire package before patching."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6875
msgid "``spack restage``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6877
msgid "Restores the source code to pristine state, as it was before building."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6879
msgid "Does this in one of two ways:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6881
msgid ""
"If the source was fetched as a tarball, deletes the entire build directory "
"and re-expands the tarball."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6884
msgid ""
"If the source was checked out from a repository, this deletes the build "
"directory and checks it out again."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6891
msgid "``spack clean``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6893
msgid ""
"Cleans up Spack's temporary and cached files.  This command can be used to "
"recover disk space if temporary files from interrupted or failed installs "
"accumulate."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6897
msgid ""
"When called with ``--stage`` or without arguments this removes all staged "
"files."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6900
msgid ""
"The ``--downloads`` option removes cached :ref:`cached <caching>` downloads."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6902
msgid ""
"You can force the removal of all install failure tracking markers using the "
"``--failures`` option.  Note that ``spack install`` will automatically clear "
"relevant failure markings prior to performing the requested installation(s)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6906
msgid ""
"Long-lived caches, like the virtual package index, are removed using the ``--"
"misc-cache`` option."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6909
msgid ""
"The ``--python-cache`` option removes `.pyc`, `.pyo`, and `__pycache__` "
"folders."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6912
msgid "To remove all of the above, the command can be called with ``--all``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6914
msgid ""
"When called with positional arguments, this command cleans up temporary "
"files only for a particular package. If ``fetch``, ``stage``, or ``install`` "
"are run again after this, Spack's build process will start from scratch."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6921
msgid "Keeping the stage directory on success"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6923
msgid ""
"By default, ``spack install`` will delete the staging area once a package "
"has been successfully built and installed.  Use ``--keep-stage`` to leave "
"the build directory intact:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6927
msgid "$ spack install --keep-stage <spec>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6931
msgid ""
"This allows you to inspect the build directory and potentially debug the "
"build.  You can use ``clean`` later to get rid of the unwanted temporary "
"files."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6937
msgid "Keeping the install prefix on failure"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6939
msgid ""
"By default, ``spack install`` will delete any partially constructed install "
"prefix if anything fails during ``install()``.  If you want to keep the "
"prefix anyway (e.g. to diagnose a bug), you can use ``--keep-prefix``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6944
msgid "$ spack install --keep-prefix <spec>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6948
msgid ""
"Note that this may confuse Spack into thinking that the package has been "
"installed properly, so you may need to use ``spack uninstall --force`` to "
"get rid of the install prefix before you build again:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6952
msgid "$ spack uninstall --force <spec>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6958
msgid "Graphing dependencies"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6964
msgid "``spack graph``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6966
msgid ""
"Spack provides the ``spack graph`` command for graphing dependencies. The "
"command by default generates an ASCII rendering of a spec's dependency "
"graph.  For example:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6972
msgid ""
"At the top is the root package in the DAG, with dependency edges emerging "
"from it.  On a color terminal, the edges are colored by which dependency "
"they lead to."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6978
msgid ""
"The ``deptype`` argument tells Spack what types of dependencies to graph. By "
"default it includes link and run dependencies but not build dependencies.  "
"Supplying ``--deptype=link`` will show only link dependencies.  The default "
"is ``--deptype=all``, which is equivalent to ``--deptype=build,link,run,"
"test``.  Options for ``deptype`` include:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6984
msgid ""
"Any combination of ``build``, ``link``, ``run``, and ``test`` separated by "
"commas."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6986
msgid "``all`` for all types of dependencies."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6988
msgid ""
"You can also use ``spack graph`` to generate graphs in the widely used `Dot "
"<http://www.graphviz.org/doc/info/lang.html>`_ format.  For example:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6993
msgid ""
"This graph can be provided as input to other graphing tools, such as those "
"in `Graphviz <http://www.graphviz.org>`_.  If you have graphviz installed, "
"you can write straight to PDF like this:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:6997
msgid "$ spack graph --dot hdf5 | dot -Tpdf > hdf5.pdf"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:7005
msgid "Interactive shell support"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:7007
msgid ""
"Spack provides some limited shell support to make life easier for "
"packagers.  You can enable these commands by sourcing a setup file in the "
"``share/spack`` directory.  For ``bash`` or ``ksh``, run:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:7011
msgid ""
"export SPACK_ROOT=/path/to/spack\n"
". $SPACK_ROOT/share/spack/setup-env.sh"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:7016
msgid "For ``csh`` and ``tcsh`` run:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:7018
msgid ""
"setenv SPACK_ROOT /path/to/spack\n"
"source $SPACK_ROOT/share/spack/setup-env.csh"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:7023
msgid "``spack cd`` will then be available."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:7029
msgid "``spack cd``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:7031
msgid ""
"``spack cd`` allows you to quickly cd to pertinent directories in Spack. "
"Suppose you've staged a package but you want to modify it before you build "
"it:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:7035
msgid ""
"$ spack stage libelf\n"
"==> Trying to fetch from http://www.mr511.de/software/libelf-0.8.13.tar.gz\n"
"######################################################################## "
"100.0%\n"
"==> Staging archive: ~/spack/var/spack/stage/libelf@0.8.13%gcc@4.8.3 "
"arch=linux-debian7-x86_64/libelf-0.8.13.tar.gz\n"
"==> Created stage in ~/spack/var/spack/stage/libelf@0.8.13%gcc@4.8.3 "
"arch=linux-debian7-x86_64.\n"
"$ spack cd libelf\n"
"$ pwd\n"
"~/spack/var/spack/stage/libelf@0.8.13%gcc@4.8.3 arch=linux-debian7-x86_64/"
"libelf-0.8.13"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:7046
msgid ""
"``spack cd`` here changed the current working directory to the directory "
"containing the expanded ``libelf`` source code.  There are a number of other "
"places you can cd to in the spack directory hierarchy:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:7052
msgid ""
"Some of these change directory into package-specific locations (stage "
"directory, install directory, package directory) and others change to core "
"spack locations.  For example, ``spack cd --module-dir`` will take you to "
"the main python source directory of your spack install."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:7061
msgid "``spack build-env``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:7063
msgid ""
"``spack build-env`` functions much like the standard unix ``build-env`` "
"command, but it takes a spec as an argument.  You can use it to see the "
"environment variables that will be set when a particular build runs, for "
"example:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:7068
msgid "$ spack build-env mpileaks@1.1%intel"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:7072
msgid ""
"This will display the entire environment that will be set when the "
"``mpileaks@1.1%intel`` build runs."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:7075
msgid ""
"To run commands in a package's build environment, you can simply provide "
"them after the spec argument to ``spack build-env``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:7078
msgid ""
"$ spack cd mpileaks@1.1%intel\n"
"$ spack build-env mpileaks@1.1%intel ./configure"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:7083
msgid ""
"This will cd to the build directory and then run ``configure`` in the "
"package's build environment."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:7090
msgid "``spack location``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:7092
msgid ""
"``spack location`` is the same as ``spack cd`` but it does not require shell "
"support.  It simply prints out the path you ask for, rather than cd'ing to "
"it.  In bash, this:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:7096
msgid "$ cd $(spack location --build-dir <spec>)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:7100
msgid "is the same as:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:7102
msgid "$ spack cd --build-dir <spec>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:7106
msgid ""
"``spack location`` is intended for use in scripts or makefiles that need to "
"know where packages are installed.  e.g., in a makefile you might write:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:7110
msgid ""
"DWARF_PREFIX = $(spack location --install-dir libdwarf)\n"
"CXXFLAGS += -I$DWARF_PREFIX/include\n"
"CXXFLAGS += -L$DWARF_PREFIX/lib"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:7120
msgid "Specifying ABI Compatibility"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:7122
msgid ""
"Packages can include ABI-compatibility information using the ``can_splice`` "
"directive. For example, if ``Foo`` version 1.1 can always replace version "
"1.0, then the package could have:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:7126
msgid "can_splice(\"foo@1.0\", when=\"@1.1\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:7130
msgid ""
"For virtual packages, packages can also specify ABI-compabitiliby with other "
"packages providing the same virtual. For example, ``zlib-ng`` could specify:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:7134
msgid "can_splice(\"zlib@1.3.1\", when=\"@2.2+compat\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:7138
msgid ""
"Some packages have ABI-compatibility that is dependent on matching variant "
"values, either for all variants or for some set of ABI-relevant variants. In "
"those cases, it is not necessary to specify the full combinatorial "
"explosion. The ``match_variants`` keyword can cover all single-value "
"variants."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:7144
msgid ""
"can_splice(\"foo@1.1\", when=\"@1.2\", match_variants=[\"bar\"])  # any "
"value for bar as long as they're the same\n"
"can_splice(\"foo@1.2\", when=\"@1.3\", match_variants=\"*\")  # any variant "
"values if all single-value variants match"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:7149
msgid ""
"The concretizer will use ABI compatibility to determine automatic splices "
"when :ref:`automatic splicing<automatic_splicing>` is enabled."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:7154
msgid ""
"The ``can_splice`` directive is experimental, and may be replaced by a "
"higher-level interface in future versions of Spack."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:7161
msgid "Package class architecture"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:7165
msgid ""
"This section aims to provide a high-level knowledge of how the package class "
"architecture evolved in Spack, and provides some insights on the current "
"design."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:7168
msgid ""
"Packages in Spack were originally designed to support only a single build "
"system. The overall class structure for a package looked like:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:7175
msgid ""
"In this architecture the base class ``AutotoolsPackage`` was responsible for "
"both the metadata related to the ``autotools`` build system (e.g. "
"dependencies or variants common to all packages using it), and for encoding "
"the default installation procedure."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:7179
msgid ""
"In reality, a non-negligible number of packages are either changing their "
"build system during the evolution of the project, or using different build "
"systems for different platforms. An architecture based on a single class "
"requires hacks or other workarounds to deal with these cases."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:7183
msgid ""
"To support a model more adherent to reality, Spack v0.19 changed its "
"internal design by extracting the attributes and methods related to building "
"a software into a separate hierarchy:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:7190
msgid ""
"In this new format each ``package.py`` contains one ``*Package`` class that "
"gathers all the metadata, and one or more ``*Builder`` classes that encode "
"the installation procedure. A specific builder object is created just before "
"the software is built, so at a time where Spack knows which build system "
"needs to be used for the current installation, and receives a ``package`` "
"object during initialization."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:7197
msgid "``build_system`` variant"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:7199
msgid ""
"To allow imposing conditions based on the build system, each package must a "
"have ``build_system`` variant, which is usually inherited from base classes. "
"This variant allows for writing metadata that is conditional on the build "
"system:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:7203
msgid ""
"with when(\"build_system=cmake\"):\n"
"    depends_on(\"cmake\", type=\"build\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:7208
msgid ""
"and also for selecting a specific build system from a spec literal, like in "
"the following command:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:7210
msgid "$ spack install arpack-ng build_system=autotools"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:7216
msgid "Compatibility with single-class format"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:7218
msgid ""
"Internally, Spack always uses builders to perform operations related to the "
"installation of a specific software. The builders are created in the ``spack."
"builder.create`` function"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:7221
msgid ""
"def create(pkg):\n"
"    \"\"\"Given a package object with an associated concrete spec,\n"
"    return the builder object that can install it.\n"
"\n"
"    Args:\n"
"         pkg (spack.package_base.PackageBase): package for which we want the "
"builder\n"
"    \"\"\"\n"
"    if id(pkg) not in _BUILDERS:\n"
"        _BUILDERS[id(pkg)] = _create(pkg)\n"
"    return _BUILDERS[id(pkg)]\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:7224
msgid ""
"To achieve backward compatibility with the single-class format Spack creates "
"in this function a special \"adapter builder\", if no custom builder is "
"detected in the recipe:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:7231
msgid ""
"Overall the role of the adapter is to route access to attributes of methods "
"first through the ``*Package`` hierarchy, and then back to the base class "
"builder. This is schematically shown in the diagram above, where the adapter "
"role is to \"emulate\" a method resolution order like the one represented by "
"the red arrows."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:7237
msgid "Specifying License Information"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:7239
msgid ""
"Most of the software in Spack is open source, and most open source software "
"is released under one or more `common open source licenses <https://"
"opensource.org/licenses/>`_. Specifying the license that a package is "
"released under in a project's `package.py` is good practice. To specify a "
"license, find the `SPDX identifier <https://spdx.org/licenses/>`_ for a "
"project and then add it using the license directive:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:7246
msgid "license(\"<SPDX Identifier HERE>\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:7250
msgid ""
"For example, the SPDX ID for the Apache Software License, version 2.0 is "
"``Apache-2.0``, so you'd write:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:7253
msgid "license(\"Apache-2.0\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:7257
msgid ""
"Or, for a dual-licensed package like Spack, you would use an `SPDX "
"Expression <https://spdx.github.io/spdx-spec/v2-draft/SPDX-license-"
"expressions/>`_ with both of its licenses:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:7261
msgid "license(\"Apache-2.0 OR MIT\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:7265
msgid ""
"Note that specifying a license without a when clause makes it apply to all "
"versions and variants of the package, which might not actually be the case. "
"For example, a project might have switched licenses at some point or have "
"certain build configurations that include files that are licensed "
"differently. Spack itself used to be under the ``LGPL-2.1`` license, until "
"it was relicensed in version ``0.12`` in 2018."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:7272
msgid ""
"You can specify when a ``license()`` directive applies using with a "
"``when=`` clause, just like other directives. For example, to specify that a "
"specific license identifier should only apply to versions up to ``0.11``, "
"but another license should apply for later versions, you could write:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:7277
msgid ""
"license(\"LGPL-2.1\", when=\"@:0.11\")\n"
"license(\"Apache-2.0 OR MIT\", when=\"@0.12:\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:7282
msgid ""
"Note that unlike for most other directives, the ``when=`` constraints in the "
"``license()`` directive can't intersect. Spack needs to be able to resolve "
"exactly one license identifier expression for any given version. To specify "
"*multiple* licenses, use SPDX expressions and operators as above. The "
"operators you probably care most about are:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:7288
msgid "``OR``: user chooses one license to adhere to; and"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:7289
msgid "``AND``: user has to adhere to all the licenses."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:7291
msgid ""
"You may also care about `license exceptions <https://spdx.org/licenses/"
"exceptions-index.html>`_ that use the ``WITH`` operator, e.g. ``Apache-2.0 "
"WITH LLVM-exception``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:7295
msgid ""
"Many of the licenses that are currently in the spack repositories have been "
"automatically determined. While this is great for bulk adding license "
"information and is most likely correct, there are sometimes edge cases that "
"require manual intervention. To determine which licenses are validated and "
"which are not, there is the `checked_by` parameter in the license directive:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:7301
msgid ""
"license(\"<license>\", when=\"<when>\", checked_by=\"<github username>\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide.rst:7305
msgid ""
"When you have validated a github license, either when doing so explicitly or "
"as part of packaging a new package, please set the `checked_by` parameter to "
"your Github username to signal that the license has been manually verified."
msgstr ""
